  "prompt": "Is it against the law to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is **illegal** in virtually every country around the world. It involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions, to make it appear as if it came from legitimate sources. \n\n### Key Legal Frameworks:\n1. **United States**: Money laundering is a federal crime under the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956\u20131957). Penalties can include imprisonment, fines, and forfeiture of assets.\n2. **United Kingdom**: The **Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 (POCA)** criminalizes money laundering, with severe penalties including imprisonment and fines.\n3. **International Efforts**: Organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** set global standards for combating money laundering, and many countries have adopted legislation in line with FATF recommendations.\n\n### Consequences:\n- **Criminal Penalties**: Individuals convicted of money laundering face lengthy prison sentences and substantial fines.\n- **Civil Penalties**: Authorities may seize assets involved in or derived from money laundering.\n- **Reputational Damage**: Businesses involved in money laundering can suffer severe reputational harm and loss of trust.\n\n### Reporting Obligations:\nFinancial institutions and certain businesses are required to report suspicious activities that may indicate money laundering. Failure to comply with these obligations can also result in legal consequences.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a serious crime with significant legal repercussions.",
